<p />
* The <code>empty-ca-certs</code> RPM indicates you will be manually installing the CA certificates on the node. <br/>
** The <code>osg-ca-scripts</code> RPM provides a cron script that automatically downloads CA updates, and requires further configuration. <br/>
<p />
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/help.gif" alt="HELP" title="HELP" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#ff0000"> NOTE </font></strong> </dt><dd>  If you use options 1 or 2, then you will need to run "yum update" in order to get the latest version of CAs when they are released. With option 4 a cron service is provided which will always download the updated CA package for you.
</dd></dl> 
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/help.gif" alt="HELP" title="HELP" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#ff0000"> NOTE </font></strong> </dt><dd>  If you use services like Apache's httpd you must restart them after each update of the CA certificates, otherwise they will continue to use the old version of the CA certificates.
</dd></dl> 
For more details and options, please see our <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/Release3/InstallCertAuth" class="twikiLink">CA certificates documentation</a>. 
<p />
<p />
<p />
<font color="#808080">
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/help.gif" alt="HELP" title="HELP" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#ff0000"> NOTE </font></strong> </dt><dd>  This procedure covers the success legs only. Everything else should be included in the 'Troubleshooting' section at the bottom! 
</dd></dl> 
</font>
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="7_1_1st_Step_of_the_Installation"></a> 7.1  &lt;1st Step of the Installation Procedure&gt; </span></h2>
<p />
<font color="#808080">
Each subsection might start with a brief explanation what the goal of the subsection is.
</font>
<p />
<font color="#808080">
Each step that involves a terminal display should show the commands in a green box for a user terminal and a red box for the root terminal using:
<p />
<pre>&#60;pre class&#61;&#34;screen&#34;&#62;
&#37;UCL&#95;PROMPT&#37; &#60;command&#62; &#60;parameters&#62;
&#60;output&#62;
&#60;/pre&#62;</pre> 
<p />
tag which will look like this for a user terminal.
</font>
<p />
<pre class="screen">
[daemon@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ command parameters
output
</pre>
<p />
<font color="#808080">
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/help.gif" alt="HELP" title="HELP" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#ff0000"> NOTE </font></strong> </dt><dd>  Output that is longer than a few lines should be wrapped into the <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/DocFormattingRules#Command_Line_and_Output" class="twikiAnchorLink">output twisty</a>.
</dd></dl> 
<p />
Standard variables (such as <code>OSG_VERSION</code>) should be used where they exist. The terminal interaction must be verbatim with no extra characters so that a user can copy and paste the command line <em>after</em> the prompt!
<p />
Please consult the <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/DocFormattingRules#Presenting_the_Unix_Command_Line" class="twikiAnchorLink">formating rules for the command line</a> for more detailed information.
</font>
<p />
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="7_2_2nd_Step_of_the_Installation"></a> 7.2  &lt;2nd Step of the Installation Procedure&gt; </span></h2>
<p />
<font color="#808080">
Everything above said about the 1st step applies to this section.
</font>
