<font color="#808080">
Everything said about the 1st step applies to this and every following step.
</font>
<p />
<p />
<h1><a name="9_Services"></a> 9  Services </h1>
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/help.gif" alt="HELP" title="HELP" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#ff0000"> NOTE </font></strong> </dt><dd>  This is a partial example to show what is included and the formatting.  
</dd></dl> 
Services brief description
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="9_1_Starting_and_Enabling_Servic"></a> 9.1  Starting and Enabling Services </span></h2>
<p />
To start VOMS you need to start several services: <ol>
<li>  You need to fetch the latest CA Certificate Revocation Lists (CRLs) and you should enable the fetch-crl service to keep the CRLs up to date:<pre class="rootscreen">
<font color="#ff0000"># For RHEL 5, CentOS 5, and SL5 </font>
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /usr/sbin/fetch-crl3   # This fetches the CRLs 
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/service fetch-crl3-boot start
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/service fetch-crl3-cron start
<font color="#ff0000"># For RHEL 6, CentOS 6, and SL6, or OSG 3 _older_ than 3.1.15 </font>
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /usr/sbin/fetch-crl   # This fetches the CRLs 
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/service fetch-crl-boot start
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/service fetch-crl-cron start
<font color="#ff0000"># For RHEL 7, CentOS 7, and SL7 </font>
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /usr/sbin/fetch-crl   # This fetches the CRLs 
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ systemctl start fetch-crl-boot
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ systemctl start fetch-crl-cron
</pre> For more details and options, please see our <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/Release3/InstallCertAuth#Managing_Certificate_Revocation" class="twikiAnchorLink">CRL documentation</a>.  
</li> <li> Start voms server<pre class="rootscreen">
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ service voms start
</pre>
</li></ol> 
<p />
<p />
You should also enable the appropriate services so that they are automatically started when your system is powered on:  <ul>
<li>  To enable the fetch-crl service to keep the CRLs up to date after reboots:<pre class="rootscreen">
<font color="#ff0000"># For RHEL 5, CentOS 5, and SL5 </font>
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/chkconfig fetch-crl3-boot on
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/chkconfig fetch-crl3-cron on
<font color="#ff0000"># For RHEL 6, CentOS 6, and SL6, or OSG 3 _older_ than 3.1.15 </font>
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/chkconfig fetch-crl-boot on
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/chkconfig fetch-crl-cron on
<font color="#ff0000"># For RHEL 7, CentOS 7, and SL7 </font>
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ systemctl enable fetch-crl-boot
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ systemctl enable fetch-crl-cron
</pre> 
</li> <li> To enable the other services: <pre class="rootscreen">
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/chkconfig voms on
</pre>
</li></ul> 
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="9_2_Stopping_and_Disabling_Servi"></a> 9.2  Stopping and Disabling Services </span></h2>
<p />
To stop VOMS you need to stop voms,... , and also the services they use if nothing else is using them: <ol>
<li> Stop voms server<pre class="rootscreen">
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ service voms stop
</pre>
</li> <li>  To stop fetch-crl:<pre class="rootscreen">
<font color="#ff0000"># For RHEL 5, CentOS 5, and SL5 </font>
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/service fetch-crl3-boot stop
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/service fetch-crl3-cron stop
<font color="#ff0000"># For RHEL 6, CentOS 6, and SL6, or OSG 3 _older_ than 3.1.15 </font>
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/service fetch-crl-boot stop
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/service fetch-crl-cron stop
<font color="#ff0000"># For RHEL 7, CentOS 7, and SL7 </font>
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ systemctl stop fetch-crl-boot
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ systemctl stop fetch-crl-cron
</pre> For more details and options, please see our <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/Release3/InstallCertAuth#Managing_Certificate_Revocation" class="twikiAnchorLink">CRL documentation</a>.  
</li></ol> 
<p />
<p />
In addition, you can disable services by running the following commands.  However, you don't need to do this normally. <ul>
<li>  To disable the fetch-crl service:<pre class="rootscreen">
<font color="#ff0000"># For RHEL 5, CentOS 5, and SL5 </font>
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/chkconfig fetch-crl3-boot off
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/chkconfig fetch-crl3-cron off
<font color="#ff0000"># For RHEL 6, CentOS 6, and SL6, or OSG 3 _older_ than 3.1.15 </font>
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/chkconfig fetch-crl-boot off
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/chkconfig fetch-crl-cron off
<font color="#ff0000"># For RHEL 7, CentOS 7, and SL7 </font>
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ systemctl disable fetch-crl-boot
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ systemctl disable fetch-crl-cron
</pre> 
</li> <li> To disable the other services: <pre class="rootscreen">
[root@host /opt/osg-%VERSION%]$ /sbin/chkconfig voms off
</pre>
</li></ul> 
<p />
<h1><a name="10_Validation_of_Service_Operati"></a> 10  Validation of Service Operation (Optional) </h1>
<p />
<font color="#808080">
Occasionally the steps to validate the success and correct operation of an installation may be <em>non-trivial</em>. Please use this <em>optional</em> section to describe how the user can verify the success of the installation.
<p />
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/help.gif" alt="HELP" title="HELP" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#ff0000"> NOTE </font></strong> </dt><dd>  This section should not become a user guide! Please link to the applicable sections of the user documentation if the service validation requires the reader to execute a user command.
</dd></dl> 
</font>
<p />
<h1><a name="11_Troubleshooting"></a> 11  Troubleshooting </h1>
<font color="#808080">
Please include this section if you can provide useful troubleshooting information here. Use sub sections for each topic you want to address.  Include file locations in a table as shown.
</font>
